******
[1] Control
Date: Mon 9 Mar 2009
From: Daniel Bausch <dbausch@tulane.edu>


Re: ProMED-mail Lassa fever - Nigeria (04): control 20090306.0937
-----------------------------------------------------------------
Various programs in eastern Sierra Leone, where Lassa fever is
hyperendemic, have recommended (and sometimes supplied) cats as a
control measure. Cats would seem easier to acquire and maintain as
domestic pets than [mongooses]. It is a logical step (and there is no
evidence that cats or mongooses carry or transmit Lassa virus -- a
question that often comes up), but has never been objectively evaluated.

--
Daniel G Bausch, MD, MPH&TM
Associate Professor
Director, Tulane Lassa Fever Research Program in West Africa
Department of Tropical Medicine, SL-17
J Bennet Johnston Building, Rm 511
Tulane School of Public Health and Tropical Medicine
1430 Tulane Ave
New Orleans LA 70112
USA
<dbausch@tulane.edu>

